T*
(The best time to prune your dependency tree was three years ago. The second best time is right) Tj
T*
(now. Every package in your lockfile is a door someone else holds the key to. Install scripts) Tj
T*
(run on your CI with whatever credentials your CI has, the maintainer?s account can be phished) Tj
T*
(or the registry entry handed to a new owner, and the next patch release can be something quite) Tj
T*
(different from the last one. A dependency you stopped calling two refactors ago is exposed to) Tj
T*
(all of that exactly as much as one you hit on every request, and you still get paged when a CVE) Tj
T*
(lands in it. The cheapest supply-chain hardening you can do is to stop supplying yourself with) Tj
T*
(things you don?t use. Lately my first response to a Dependabot CVE alert, and a fair few of the) Tj
T*
(routine version bumps, has been to check whether I still need the dependency at all before) Tj
T*
(looking at what changed in it. A CVE in something I barely use is a better reason to delete it) Tj
T*
(than to patch it, and ripping it out closes that alert and all the future ones at the same) Tj
T*
(time. You don?t need any tooling for that beyond the alert itself. Most of the existing writing) Tj
